It's an increasingly unstable world we live in, where businesses once considered "reliable"
and "trustworthy" can be taken out singlehandedly by the ultra-rich. Where companies previously
led by people considered "visionaries" are now having their mental capabilities (and products)
rotted by generative AI. As a result, I have taken to self-hosting. To taking it (my data/my money)
back from them (the rich/corporate overlords/tyrants).

I will eventually get into the "what" and the "how", but we can start with the why. I think
there are a lot of good reasons why I made this effort, and I'm sure there are many more
for situations I haven't even considered.

### Data ownership

Maybe the most critical benefit is the ownership I now hold over my data. With the increasing
institutionalized acceptance of the theft and sale of users' information and intellectual
property, it brings me some comfort to know that the data I store for my self-hosted services
is under my own control.

When it comes data that are want to be private, I now know exactly where that data is and how
it's stored; who has access to it and from where. If I want that data to be encrypted, I can encrypt it.
When I need this data destroyed, I can do so. Although it's now up to me to ensure that the
security is sufficient and I know that I cannot claim to be a security expert, I also know that
neither are the people we call "professional", working at the big companies,
resulting in [this list][breaches] being very long. I've also met plenty of coworkers, past
and present. I have seen firsthand how knowledgeable about security most people are. I'd
like to think I work with better-than-average developers, and I wouldn't necessarily trust
their implementation of security any better than my own. When the security is up to
me (and the consequences are all mine as well) I know exactly how much risk I am willing to
take, and how much careful planning I have put in to get it right.

[breaches]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_data_breaches

Even for data that's already and intentionally public, there are still benefits to managing that
data on my own hardware. While right now there is realistically little reason why any existing
service provider would wish to take down content which I have posted (and I have no intention
of getting into such content as would get my access to such services interrupted), it is worth
considering the possibility of the service itself changing its own terms or functionality at
any time.

We can hardly say we haven't seen it before, just look at Twitter [sic]; one day it is a
relatively normal social media platform, the next it is taken over by some volatile individual
such that we have no idea what topic will be censored next in accordance to one rich guy's
personal ideologies and whims. Although this hardly affects me personally, it's a matter of
principle: we, the people, should be allowed to own and share and maintain access to the
content that we produce and consume, regardless of the personal feelings of the people in power.
While I may not currently be affected by any of this, and still might never be personally, if
someday these self-hosted alternatives can fill in the gaps for any family or friends who are
part of groups targeted by such unjust restrictions, that's a cause I can get behind.

For less political reasons as well, sometimes some data I like or use disappears for something mundane
but beyond my control. A developer might turn their repository private; if I were to depend
so strongly on such a project, I might wish to have kept a copy of the code for myself to ensure
I am not disrupted. Streaming services regularly lose the licenses to parts of their libraries,
whereas if I happened to have a copy of that work (legitimately obtained of course), and had a place to store it
and serve it from, I would still be able to watch it and share it with people around me who might
also want it. In this world of receiving only a [license to virtual content][riot], we should take
every opportunity to just own something instead.

[riot]: https://www.riotgames.com/en/terms-of-service#:~:text=4.1.

### Sustained availability

Possibly even more fundamental than just the ownership and availability of the data is the fact
that any existing hosted service can disappear (or become a paid subscription) at any time. While it's
sometimes hard to remember them, this happens all the time, in ways that actually do affect me and
the people I know:
* I was using [Inbox][], then it was gone. Google is notorious for [killing services][killedbygoogle].
* [Firefox Send][] was a useful service that disappeared, not that I used it often but when you need this kind of thing, it's nice to have available.
* YouTube used to be entirely free, now it's riddled with ads and requires a paid subscription to remove them.
* [Miiverse][], [Vine][], [Tiktok][] (temporarily)... the list just goes on.

