[killedbygoogle]: https://killedbygoogle.com/
[Firefox Send]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Firefox_Send
[Miiverse]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miiverse
[Vine]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vine_(service)
[Tiktok]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efforts_to_ban_TikTok_in_the_United_States#2025_shutdown

A lot of services aren't that important (I can live, sadly, without Miiverse), but occasionally something
like [RememBear][] disappears; going from being used daily to leaving people without their passwords and forcing
people to reevaluate and migrate to another platform. This kind of thing can be a relative nightmare to recover from,
and it never comes at a good time.

[RememBear]: https://help.remembear.com/hc/en-us/articles/7072551070363-Ending-support-for-RememBear

Meanwhile, a fully self-hosted service will never really go away, unless I choose for it to go away. For
as long as I continue to like it, my password manager will remain where it is, and I know I won't be
forced to migrate anymore. (The same doesn't necessarily go for any others who use a service I am hosting,
but if they wanted that guarantee... it's called *self*-hosting for a reason.)

Once again, the circumstances by which a service disappears can be entirely reasonable
financially or legally based constraints, but can also be driven by [local politics][ona],
or physical location, or any other of a number of reasons that don't necessarily
fit within an individual's controllable existence. I'm fortunate enough to live in a country that doesn't apply
[nationwide Internet censorship][gfw], but this doesn't mean we won't ever be affected by even
["seemingly well-meaning" efforts][Piracy Shield], or that we'll never have some
new strongly-opinioned individual enter the realm of influence over what seemed like a
stable government and suggest taking away things we might once have considered within our rights.
You just never know.

[ona]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Online_News_Act
[Piracy Shield]: https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piracy_shield
[gfw]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Firewall

The other thing that takes a service away, even if it is actually still there, is my willingness to use it.
Lately I'm trying to gradually become a more ethical consumer; avoiding giving my hard earned money
to companies who [exploit people and our planet][Amazon], or who provide their support to [military technology][spotify]
or [foreign genocide][Indigo], or even just the companies who are contributing to the plague of [AI slop][spotify-ai]
that threatens our sense of human connection (that's... most apps these days). It takes time to
free ourselves from the conveniences these institutions have hooked us with, but self-hosting my own
alternatives is one step I can take in that process, for myself and on behalf of the people around me
if they so choose to follow.

