### It's fun

The other reason, and probably the actual strongest force leading me to starting on this journey, is that it's *fun*.
As it turns out, I might be a nerd after all: collecting and installing and configuring all these things
was a good time, and is likely to remain a good time now that I am forced to maintain this patchwork machine.
It's fun and interesting, despite how incredibly annoying it can be at times when the UDP packets just
aren't getting through no matter what you try, because the feeling once you do finally solve each issue
has no comparison.

Additionally, now that the setup is (mostly) over, the result is a bunch of convenient services available to
me and the people I choose to share my them with. Fun to build, fun to use, fun to share.

### There's a lot to learn

While not something I had really gone in search of, looking back after having put in much of the work on this project
I realize I have learned *a lot* (and there's still more to go!). About running a server. About security.
About networking. About increasingly lower levels of the Linux system. About Docker. About the
hardware on which it all runs. All of this is simply interesting to discover, having gained a deeper
understanding of this aspect of the world we live in, as well as genuinely useful in my life as
a software developer and general member of a world that grows ever more reliant on technology.
This knowledge makes me better able to reason about, design, and fix complicated and secure systems
across networks; a useful skill for my job. It also allows me to identify potential threats to the
people around me in my personal life, and gives me the means by which to protect them if the need arises.

Not even to mention discovering the entire community that makes this possible; self-hosting isn't
something we do alone, rather it's something we each can do individually together. I've learned
about so much cool software written by so many cool people, who give so much to the rest of us
and ask for little to nothing in return. By using that software and participating in this cycle,
perhaps we might find our own way to contribute back in time, to share what we know with those
who helped us reach the point we're already at.

If you've read this far, maybe you want to try it too. I hope eventually to share more specifically
some of what I have discovered, but in the meantime there are plenty of existing resources; maybe look at
what people are doing on [/r/selfhosted][], or browse the nice list of apps curated by [selfh.st][] that
you might get the chance to try hosting yourself. That's where I started, and now I'm "almost done."

(I think that's a joke; I will never be done. I'm on call for all eternity now but it's self inflicted
so I can't really complain.)

